NUTRACETICALS FUNCTIONAL FOODS: FRUITS AND VEGETABLES
Antioxidants:
1. Vitamin C: Found in citrus fruits, strawberries, kiwi, bell peppers. Benefits include immune
support, collagen production, and protection against free radicals.
2. Vitamin E: Found in nuts, seeds, and leafy greens. It helps protect cells from damage caused
by free radicals and supports immune function.
3. Beta-carotene: Found in carrots, sweet potatoes, spinach, and kale. It's converted into
vitamin A in the body and supports eye health, immune function, and skin health.
4. Lycopene: Found in tomatoes, watermelon, pink grapefruit. It's associated with reduced risk
of certain cancers, heart disease, and eye conditions.
5. Flavonoids: Found in various fruits and vegetables, including berries, apples, onions, and
broccoli. They have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, supporting heart health
and reducing the risk of chronic diseases.
Phytochemicals:
1. Anthocyanins: Found in blueberries, blackberries, cherries, and purple grapes. They have
antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, supporting brain health and reducing the risk
of heart disease.
2. Isoflavones: Found in soybeans and soy products. They have estrogen-like effects and are
associated with reduced risk of certain cancers and improved bone health.
3. Glucosinolates: Found in cruciferous vegetables like broccoli, cabbage, and Brussels sprouts.
They have anti-cancer properties and support detoxification processes in the body.
4. Quercetin: Found in apples, onions, and citrus fruits. It has antioxidant and anti-
inflammatory properties, supporting heart health and immune function.
5. Resveratrol: Found in grapes, red wine, and peanuts. It has antioxidant and anti-
inflammatory properties and may support heart health and longevity.
Health Benefits:
• Reduced risk of chronic diseases such as heart disease, diabetes, and certain cancers.
• Improved immune function.
• Better skin health and aging.
• Support for eye health and vision.
• Enhanced cognitive function and brain health.
• Reduced inflammation and oxidative stress in the body.

APPLE: The major product from apple processing is apple juice. The entire fruit is usually pressed in a
cold press to extract the juice from the fruit. Unlike cereals, there is a higher percentage of the soluble
fibre fraction in apple fibre, thus giving rise to the availability of the polymer pectin.

• Apples contain a higher percentage of soluble fiber compared to cereals, leading to the
availability of pectin.
• Pectin exhibits properties such as gelling, thickening, and stabilization in foods.
• It is considered a health-enhancing polymer, potentially lowering cholesterol and delaying
gastric emptying.
• Apple peels are rich in calcium and magnesium.
• Apple pomace is a good source of polyphenols, primarily found in the peels, with limited
extraction into the juice.
• Apples contain phenolic acids such as chlorogenic, protocatechuic, and caffeic acid.
• Polyphenols like flavonoids, including flavanols and flavonols, are present.
• Significant compounds include chlorogenic acid, phloridzin, and various quercetin glycosides,
with quercetin 3-galactoside being the predominant flavonol.
• Derivatives of flavanols, such as catechins and procyanidins, are also present in substantial
amounts.
Health Benefits:
• The apple peel contains higher levels of zinc, iron, and copper compared to the flesh.
• Minerals like iron, copper, and manganese work synergistically as effective catalysts in
preventing diseases such as atherosclerosis.
• Phytochemicals in apples are linked to health benefits such as inhibiting cancer cell
proliferation, reducing lipid oxidation, and lowering cholesterol.
• These beneficial phytochemicals help reduce the incidence of chronic diseases common in
Western countries, including heart disease, obesity, and cancer.
• Phenolic acids, like chlorogenic acid, exhibit high alkyl peroxyl radical scavenging activity,
providing a protective effect against cancer.
• Procyanidins possess high antioxidant activity and inhibit low-density lipoprotein (LDL)
oxidation.
Grapes: Components and Health Benefits
Components:
• Grape pomace yields various products such as ethanol, tartaric acid, citric acid, grape seed oil,
hydrocolloids, and dietary fiber.
• Key constituents include anthocyanins, catechins, flavonol glycosides, phenolic acids,
alcohols, and stilbenes.
• Anthocyanins are particularly valuable.
• Grape skin tannins primarily consist of catechin, epicatechin, epicatechin gallate, and
epigallocatechin.
• Grape seeds are rich in polyphenols, especially procyanidins, which act as strong antioxidants
and promote health.
• Supplementing grape juice with grape seeds increases catechin and procyanidin levels in
wines.
• Major anthocyanins in red grape pomace include cyanidin, peonidin, delphinidin, petunidin,
and malvidin, with quercetin as the main flavonol.
• The primary phenolic acid present is gallic acid.
Health Benefits:

• Polyphenols like anthocyanins and flavonoids are linked to reduced cardiovascular disease
(CVD) and some cancers.
• They enhance plasma antioxidant capacity, inhibiting LDL oxidation.
• Polyphenols help lower systolic blood pressure and plasma levels.
• Grape pomace is a rich source of these beneficial polyphenols.
• Flavonoids react with harmful radicals, reducing lipid oxidation.
• Reducing lipid oxidation extends product shelf-life, adding health benefits to grape pomace
use.
Mango:
• Both ripe and unripe mango peels are rich in polyphenols, with ß-carotene being the
prominent carotenoid.
• 'Tommy Atkins' mango peels, in particular, are abundant in flavonol glycosides, a subgroup of
polyphenols known as flavonoids.
• Red-colored mango cultivars contain notable levels of anthocyanins.
• Mango peels, especially when ripened, provide antioxidants like vitamin C and vitamin E,
effectively scavenging free radicals, preventing DNA oxidative damage, and inhibiting cell
communication inhibition.
• Adding mango peel to food products enhances their nutritional value by increasing dietary
fiber and phytochemical levels without compromising quality.
Lemon:
• After extracting juice and essential oil from lemons, about 50% of the original fruit remains as
by-products, including peels (albedo and flavedo), seeds, and fruit pulp.
• Lemons, like most citrus fruits, are abundant in antioxidants and polyphenols.
• Lemon juice is a rich source of ascorbic acid, aiding in iron absorption, hormonal regulation,
and cellular oxidoreduction processes.
• Significant levels of flavonoids, particularly flavanones and flavones, are present in lemons,
along with carotenoids, albeit in lower quantities.
• Hesperidin, a specific flavonoid found in lemons, shows promise in treating rheumatoid
arthritis.
ORANGES
1. Vitamin C: Oranges are renowned for their high vitamin C content, which is essential for
immune function, collagen synthesis, and wound healing. It also acts as an antioxidant,
protecting cells from damage caused by free radicals.
2. Fiber: Oranges are rich in dietary fiber, including soluble fiber like pectin. Fiber promotes
digestive health, helps regulate blood sugar levels, and aids in weight management by
promoting feelings of fullness.
3. Flavonoids (including Hesperidin): Oranges contain flavonoids like hesperidin, which have
antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. They may help reduce inflammation, improve
blood vessel function, and lower blood pressure.
4. Citric Acid: Citric acid, abundant in oranges, can aid in kidney stone prevention by increasing
urinary citrate levels, which inhibits the formation of certain types of kidney stones.
5. Carotenoids (Beta-Carotene): Oranges contain carotenoids like beta-carotene, which is
converted into vitamin A in the body. Vitamin A is essential for vision, immune function, and
skin health.
4 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
6. Potassium: Oranges are a good source of potassium, an electrolyte that helps regulate fluid
balance, nerve function, and muscle contractions. Adequate potassium intake is associated
with lower blood pressure and reduced risk of stroke.
7. Folate (Vitamin B9): Oranges provide folate, a B vitamin important for DNA synthesis and cell
division. Adequate folate intake is crucial during pregnancy for preventing neural tube defects
in the developing fetus.
8. Thiamine (Vitamin B1): Oranges contain thiamine, which plays a vital role in energy
metabolism and nerve function. It's essential for converting carbohydrates into energy.
health benefits
Immune Support: Vitamin C in oranges boosts the immune system, helping the body fight off
infections and illnesses.
1. Heart Health: The fiber, potassium, and flavonoids in oranges can help lower cholesterol
levels, regulate blood pressure, and reduce the risk of heart disease.
2. Digestive Health: The fiber content aids digestion, prevents constipation, and promotes a
healthy gut microbiome.
3. Cancer Prevention: The antioxidants, including vitamin C and flavonoids, may help reduce the
risk of certain cancers by neutralizing free radicals and inhibiting the growth of cancer cells.
4. Skin Health: Vitamin C promotes collagen production, contributing to healthier skin and
wound healing. Antioxidants in oranges also protect the skin from sun damage and premature
aging.
5. Eye Health: The beta-carotene and vitamin A content support vision and may help prevent
age-related macular degeneration.
6. Bone Health: Oranges contain nutrients like calcium and vitamin D, which are essential for
maintaining strong bones and preventing osteoporosis.
7. Weight Management: The fiber content and low calorie count of oranges can aid in weight
loss and weight management by promoting satiety and reducing calorie intake.
8. Kidney Stone Prevention: Citric acid in oranges may help prevent the formation of kidney
stones by increasing urinary citrate levels.
9. Brain Health: Flavonoids and other antioxidants in oranges may improve cognitive function
and protect against age-related cognitive decline.
CHLOROPHYLL is a green pigment found in plants and algae that plays a critical role in
photosynthesis, the process by which plants convert light energy into chemical energy. It absorbs light
primarily in the blue and red wavelengths and reflects green light, giving plants their characteristic
green color. Chlorophyll has many forms such as chlorophyll a,chlorophyll b, chlorophyll c, chlorophyll
d and chlorophyll e
Types of Chlorophyll:
1. Chlorophyll a: This is the primary type of chlorophyll found in plants and algae. It absorbs light
most efficiently in the blue and red parts of the spectrum and reflects green light, giving
plants their green color.
2. Chlorophyll b: This is another type of chlorophyll found in plants and algae. It absorbs light in
slightly different wavelengths than chlorophyll a and helps complement its light-absorbing
capabilities.
5 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
3. Chlorophyll c: This type of chlorophyll is found in certain types of algae and marine plants. It
absorbs light in different wavelengths compared to chlorophylls a and b, allowing organisms
to utilize light energy in deeper waters.
4. Chlorophyll d: Discovered in 2010, chlorophyll d is found in certain cyanobacteria living in
environments with low light. It absorbs light in the infrared region, allowing organisms to
harness light energy that would otherwise be unusable.
5. Chlorophyll e: Chlorophyll e is found in a few organisms, particularly certain green algae. It
also absorbs light in different wavelengths compared to chlorophylls a and b, expanding the
range of light that can be utilized for photosynthesis.

CHLOROPHYLLIN is a water-soluble derivative of chlorophyll, the green pigment
found in plants and algae. It is often used as a dietary supplement or food additive due to its potential
health benefits and deodorizing properties.
Chlorophyllin, a water-soluble derivative of chlorophyll, is frequently utilized as an additive in
medications or food dyes. It's essentially a semi-synthetic version of chlorophyll, known specifically as
a copper trisodium salt of 3-[(2-carboxymethyl)-18-(dioxido-methylidene)-8-beta-hydroxy-2-
naphthaleneethylidene]-porphyrinato(2-) Schiff base.
TYPES
1. Copper Chlorophyllin: This type of chlorophyllin contains copper as the central metal ion. It is
the most widely used form of chlorophyllin and is often used in dietary supplements, food
additives, and personal care products.
2. Sodium Copper Chlorophyllin: In this type, the copper ion is complexed with sodium. It is also
commonly used in dietary supplements and food coloring agents.
SOURCE
1. Chlorophyllin, a synthesized derivative of chlorophyll, is not naturally occurring in plants but is
extracted from chlorophyll-containing sources like algae, notably Spirulina platensis, available
commercially.
2. Chlorophylls are sourced from green fruits and vegetables in the human diet, with their
content varying due to factors such as maturity stage, growing conditions, harvest time, plant
parts used, storage conditions, food processing methods, and extraction and quantification
techniques.
3. Primary sources of chlorophyll include leafy green vegetables such as kale, spinach, and Swiss
chard, as well as broccoli, cabbage, cress, dill, golden apple, green apple, green bean, green
bell pepper, kiwi, lettuce, mint, parsley, purple basil, scallion, zucchini, alfalfa sprouts, and
seaweeds like chlorella and spirulina.
Chlorophyll pigment offers numerous health benefits to the body:
1. Antioxidant Properties: Chlorophyll acts as an antioxidant, reducing oxidative stress and
protecting endocrine organs from damage caused by endocrine disruptors.
2. Skin Health: Chlorophyll reduces skin inflammation, aids in cell repair, cleanses the skin, and
protects against oxidative damage. It contains vitamins A, C, E, and K, crucial for maintaining
radiant and youthful skin, along with magnesium for skin nourishment.
3. Acne Treatment: Topical chlorophyll shows promise in reducing acne lesions and oily skin.
4. Detoxification: Chlorophyll binds to and removes harmful chemicals from the body, aiding in
the prevention of damage caused by carcinogens and toxins.
5. Anti-Cancer Potential: Chlorophyll may reduce cancerous tumor occurrence by blocking
absorption of carcinogenic chemicals like aflatoxins and preventing damage to genes.
6. Wound Healing: Chlorophyll stimulates tissue regeneration and reduces inflammation,
promoting wound healing.
7. Blood-Building Properties: Chemically similar to hemoglobin, chlorophyll may help treat
hemoglobin deficiency disorders like anemia and thalassemia.
8. Deodorant Properties: Chlorophyll may reduce body odor and bad breath when consumed or
applied topically.
9. Potential Weight Loss Aid: Some studies suggest chlorophyll promotes satiety and supports
metabolism, potentially aiding in weight loss.

10. Hormonal Balance: Chlorophyll may support hormonal balance, benefiting conditions like
acne, PMS, and menopausal symptoms.
11. Arthritis Relief: Chlorophyll's anti-inflammatory properties may reduce inflammation and pain
associated with arthritis.
12. Energy Boost: Chlorophyll enhances oxygen uptake and cellular function, potentially
combating fatigue and promoting vitality.
CAROTENOIDS are a group of pigments found in plants, algae, and photosynthetic bacteria. They
are responsible for the yellow, orange, and red colors seen in many fruits, vegetables, and other
organisms. Carotenoids play essential roles in photosynthesis and also have health benefits for
humans.
There are two main types of carotenoids:
1. Carotenes: Carotenes are hydrocarbons, meaning they consist solely of carbon and hydrogen
atoms. They are typically orange or red pigments. The most well-known carotene is beta-
carotene, which is a precursor to vitamin A in the human body. Other carotenes include
alpha-carotene and lycopene.
2. Xanthophylls: Xanthophylls are oxygen-containing carotenoids, making them more polar than
carotenes. They often have yellow pigmentation. Some common xanthophylls include lutein,
zeaxanthin, and astaxanthin. Xanthophylls are known for their antioxidant properties and are
important for eye health, particularly in protecting against age-related macular degeneration.
sources rich in carotenoids:
1. Starchy Vegetables: Pumpkin, sweet potatoes, squash, carrots, and other root vegetables.
2. Dark Leafy Greens: Spinach, kale, collard greens, Swiss chard.
3. Fruits: Tomatoes, watermelon, cantaloupe, apricots, mangoes, oranges.
4. Other Vegetables: Bell peppers, broccoli, corn, summer squash, zucchini, peas.
5. Red and Orange Fruits: Papaya, pink grapefruit, guava, rose hips.
6. Root Crops: Garnet yams, beets.
7. Legumes: Pistachios.
8. Miscellaneous: Avocados, eggs (especially egg yolks), cooked crab, and certain fish like wild
salmon.
Health Benefits of Carotenoids
Eye Health:
• Lutein and zeaxanthin protect against age-related macular degeneration (AMD) and cataracts.
• Their antioxidant properties help reduce oxidative stress within photoreceptors, guarding
against impairment and blindness in the elderly.
Heart Health:
• Carotenoids act as antioxidants, reducing oxidative stress and protecting against ROS-
mediated disorders like atherosclerosis.
• Certain carotenoids like astaxanthin, lutein, or beta-cryptoxanthin are particularly beneficial
for cardiovascular health.
Cancer Prevention:
8 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
• Various carotenoids, such as beta-carotene, lutein, and lycopene, are associated with a
decreased risk of lung, prostate, oral, pharynx, larynx, esophageal, and colon cancers.
• Beta-carotene and lycopene act as efficient scavengers of ROS generated by UV radiation,
potentially reducing the risk of skin cancer.
Immune System Support:
• Some carotenoids can be converted into vitamin A, essential for immune function.
• Vitamin A deficiency increases the risk of severe infections like measles.
UV Protection for Skin:
• Carotenoids like lycopene can break down into vitamin A, offering protection against
premature skin damage from sun exposure and reducing the risk of skin cancer and
premature aging.
Improved Cognitive Function:
• Carotenoids contribute to improved cognitive performance and overall brain health.
LYCOPENE is a naturally occurring chemical compound that belongs to the class of carotenoids. It is
a pigment responsible for the red color in fruits and vegetables like tomatoes, watermelon, pink
grapefruit, and papaya. Lycopene is a potent antioxidant, meaning it helps neutralize harmful free
radicals in the body, which are associated with various chronic diseases and aging. Research suggests
that consuming lycopene-rich foods may offer health benefits such as reducing the risk of certain
cancers, promoting heart health, and supporting overall well-being.
SOURCE
1. Tomatoes: Especially concentrated in cooked or processed tomato products like
tomato paste, tomato sauce, and tomato juice.
2. Watermelon: Particularly ripe, red watermelon contains significant amounts of
lycopene.
3. Pink Grapefruit: This citrus fruit contains lycopene in its pink or red flesh.
4. Guava: Both pink and red guavas are good sources of lycopene.
5. Papaya: The red and pink varieties of papaya contain lycopene.
6. Red Bell Peppers: Though not as high in lycopene as tomatoes, red bell peppers still
contain notable amounts.
7. Apricots: Some apricot varieties contain lycopene, especially those with a darker red
or pink color.
Health benefits of Lycopene
1. Antioxidant Properties: Lycopene acts as a potent antioxidant, helping to neutralize harmful
free radicals in the body. This may reduce oxidative stress and lower the risk of chronic
diseases such as cancer and cardiovascular disease.
9 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
2. Heart Health: Some studies suggest that lycopene may help lower levels of LDL (bad)
cholesterol and reduce the risk of heart disease. It may also help improve the function of
blood vessels.
3. Cancer Prevention: Lycopene has been studied for its potential role in preventing certain
types of cancer, particularly prostate cancer. Some research indicates that a diet rich in
lycopene-containing foods may lower the risk of developing prostate, lung, and stomach
cancers.
4. Eye Health: Lycopene is thought to play a role in maintaining eye health and preventing age-
related macular degeneration (AMD), a leading cause of vision loss in older adults.
5. Skin Protection: Lycopene may help protect the skin from sun damage by reducing the risk of
sunburn and decreasing UV-induced skin redness. It may also help improve skin texture and
reduce signs of aging such as wrinkles.
6. Bone Health: Some studies suggest that lycopene may help improve bone health by reducing
bone loss and increasing bone density, potentially lowering the risk of osteoporosis.
7. Anti-inflammatory Effects: Lycopene may possess anti-inflammatory properties, which could
help reduce inflammation throughout the body and lower the risk of chronic diseases
associated with inflammation, such as arthritis and certain types of cancer.
8. Brain Health: Preliminary research indicates that lycopene may have neuroprotective effects
and could help reduce the risk of neurodegenerative diseases like Alzheimer's disease.
9. Colorectal Cancer: Low levels of lycopene in the blood increase the risk of colorectal
adenomas, which are precursors to colorectal cancer. Smoking and low lycopene levels
significantly raise this risk.
10. Prostate Cancer: Lycopene, found in tomatoes, may help prevent cancer by neutralizing free
radicals, influencing cell signaling pathways, and inhibiting cancer cell growth. It's particularly
effective in reducing the incidence of mammary tumors and inhibiting cancer cells stimulated
by insulin-like growth factor type 1.
11. Pancreatic Cancer: Consuming lycopene is associated with a lower risk of pancreatic cancer.
Lycopene activates cancer-preventive enzymes, reducing cancer risk. It also protects against
DNA damage and oxidative stress.
12. Coronary Heart Diseases: Regular consumption of lycopene-rich foods lowers the risk of
cardiovascular disease (CVD). Lycopene reduces LDL cholesterol oxidation, enhances
endothelial function, and protects against oxidative stress and DNA damage, contributing to
heart health.
Anthocyanins: Definition: Anthocyanins are water-soluble pigments that belong to the
flavonoid group of phytochemicals. They are synthesized via the phenylpropanoid pathway in plants
and are responsible for providing red, purple, and blue hues to many fruits, vegetables, and flowers.
1. Types of Anthocyanins:
o Cyanidin: Cyanidin is one of the most common anthocyanins found in nature. It
imparts a red to purple color and is abundant in foods like berries (e.g., strawberries,
raspberries, blackberries), cherries, red cabbage, and grapes.
o Delphinidin: Delphinidin produces a blue to purple color and is found in foods like
blueberries, cranberries, blackcurrants, and Concord grapes.
o Pelargonidin: Pelargonidin contributes to orange to red hues and is present in foods
like strawberries, raspberries, cherries, and red apples.
o Petunidin: Petunidin produces purple to black colors and is found in foods like
blackberries, blueberries, raspberries, grapes, and blackcurrants.
o Malvidin: Malvidin imparts red to purple hues and is abundant in foods like grapes
(especially red and purple varieties), blackberries, blueberries, and strawberries.
10 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
o Peonidin: Peonidin contributes to red to purple colors and is found in foods like
strawberries, raspberries, red apples, and red cabbage.
SOURCE
1. Berries: Blueberries, strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, and cranberries are rich sources
of anthocyanins. These fruits contain varying levels of different types of anthocyanins,
contributing to their vibrant colors and health benefits.
2. Grapes: Both red and purple grapes contain anthocyanins, particularly malvidin and
delphinidin. Red wine is also a source of anthocyanins due to the presence of grape skins
during the fermentation process.
3. Cherries: Cherries, especially darker varieties like tart cherries, contain anthocyanins such as
cyanidin and peonidin.
4. Plums and Prunes: Plums and prunes (dried plums) are rich in anthocyanins, particularly
cyanidin and peonidin.
5. Red Cabbage: Red cabbage contains anthocyanins that contribute to its purple-red color.
Other purple or blue-hued vegetables like purple potatoes and purple carrots also contain
anthocyanins.
6. Eggplant: The skin of eggplants contains anthocyanins, giving it a deep purple color.
7. Blackcurrants: Blackcurrants are particularly rich in anthocyanins, especially delphinidin and
cyanidin.
8. Blood Oranges: Blood oranges contain anthocyanins in their peel and pulp, contributing to
their characteristic red color.
9. Apples: Some apple varieties, especially red-skinned apples like Red Delicious and Fuji,
contain anthocyanins in their skin.
10. Red Onions: Red onions contain anthocyanins in their outer layers, which give them their
purple-red color.
HEALTH BENFITS
Antioxidant Properties: Anthocyanins have strong antioxidant effects, which means they help neutralize
harmful free radicals in the body. This can potentially reduce oxidative stress and lower the risk of chronic
diseases like heart disease, cancer, and diabetes.
Heart Health: Some studies suggest that anthocyanins may help improve heart health by reducing inflammation,
improving blood flow, and lowering blood pressure. These effects can contribute to a lower risk of
cardiovascular diseases.
Cancer Prevention: Research indicates that anthocyanins may have anticancer properties. They may help inhibit
the growth of cancer cells and promote their destruction. However, more studies are needed to fully
understand the extent of their cancer-fighting potential.
Brain Health: Anthocyanins may benefit brain health by protecting against age-related cognitive decline and
neurodegenerative diseases like Alzheimer's disease. They may help improve memory, learning, and overall
cognitive function.
Anti-Inflammatory Effects: Anthocyanins have been shown to possess anti-inflammatory properties, which can
help reduce inflammation in the body. Chronic inflammation is linked to various diseases, so consuming
anthocyanin-rich foods may help mitigate inflammation and its negative effects.
Eye Health: Some evidence suggests that anthocyanins may support eye health by protecting against age-
related vision problems such as macular degeneration and cataracts. These compounds may help maintain the
health of the retina and other structures in the eye.
11 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
• Neuroprotective Effects:
• Anthocyanins act as antioxidants, countering oxidative stress implicated in neurodegenerative diseases.
• They prevent neuronal death by scavenging mitochondrial reactive oxygen species (ROS) and may
prevent ROS production by mildly depolarizing mitochondria.
• Studies demonstrate their effectiveness in preventing neuronal death caused by different stressors like
glutamate or oxygen and glucose deprivation.
• Animal studies show that orally consumed anthocyanins, such as Cy3glc from cherries, reduce brain
superoxide levels and improve outcomes in ischemic stroke models.
Cardioprotective Effects:
• Regular intake of anthocyanins is associated with a reduced risk of cardiovascular diseases, including
coronary heart disease and myocardial infarction.
• They reduce cardiovascular disease risk, lower blood pressure, blood glucose levels, and decrease
major coronary events and cardiovascular mortality.
• Anthocyanins protect the heart by scavenging ROS and inhibiting mitochondria-mediated cell death
pathways, preventing apoptosis and necrosis.
Effects on Liver, Kidney, and Pancreas:
• Anthocyanins exhibit positive effects on the liver, kidney, and pancreas by acting against oxidative
stress, maintaining mitochondrial functions, and preventing cell apoptosis.
• Studies demonstrate their ability to reduce ROS formation, prevent mitochondrial membrane lipid
peroxidation, protect against mitochondrial swelling, and maintain membrane potential.
• They improve antioxidant enzyme activities, mitochondrial capacity, and reduce ROS levels in liver,
kidney, and pancreas cells exposed to various stressors.
BIOAVAILABILITY OF NUTRACEUTICALS
The FDA (U.S. Food and Drug Administration) defines bioavailability as "the rate and extent to
which the active ingredient or active moiety is absorbed from a drug product and becomes
available at the site of action."
The bioavailability of phytonutrients in nutraceuticals refers to the extent and rate at which
these compounds are absorbed and utilized by the body after ingestion.
FACTORS INFLUENCE THE BIOAVAILABILITY
1. Chemical Form: The chemical form of the nutraceutical can affect its absorption and
bioavailability. For instance, some compounds may be more readily absorbed in certain forms
(e.g., fat-soluble versus water-soluble).
2. Solubility: Solubility in water or fat affects how well a nutraceutical can be absorbed in the
digestive tract. Lipophilic (fat-loving) compounds may have better absorption in the presence
of dietary fat.
3. Food Matrix: Nutraceuticals consumed within foods may have different bioavailability
compared to when taken as isolated supplements. The presence of other compounds in food
can affect absorption and metabolism.
4. Digestive Processes: Factors such as gastric pH, digestive enzyme activity, and gastrointestinal
motility can influence the breakdown and absorption of nutraceuticals.
12 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
5. Interaction with Other Nutrients: Some nutrients may enhance or inhibit the absorption of
others. For example, vitamin C can enhance the absorption of non-heme iron, while calcium
may interfere with the absorption of some minerals like zinc and magnesium.
6. Individual Variability: Factors such as genetics, age, sex, gut microbiota composition, and
health status can affect how well nutraceuticals are absorbed and utilized by the body.
7. Formulation and Delivery: The formulation of nutraceutical products (e.g., encapsulation,
nanoemulsions) and their delivery systems (e.g., oral, transdermal) can impact bioavailability
by affecting factors such as stability, release rate, and absorption kinetics.
8. Dose: The amount of nutraceutical consumed can influence its bioavailability. Higher doses
may saturate absorption mechanisms or undergo different metabolic pathways.
9. Processing and Storage: Processing methods and storage conditions can affect the stability
and bioavailability of nutraceuticals. Factors such as temperature, light exposure, and
oxidation can degrade these compounds.
10. Health Conditions and Medications: Certain health conditions (e.g., gastrointestinal disorders)
and medications may alter gastrointestinal function and nutrient absorption, thereby
affecting the bioavailability of nutraceuticals.
To enhance the bioavailability of nutraceuticals, researchers have developed various delivery systems
with functional properties to overcome these limitations. Here are some approaches commonly
utilized:
1. Protection of Labile Compounds: Nutraceuticals are susceptible to degradation due to factors
such as pH variations, enzymatic degradation, and mechanical movements in the GI tract.
Delivery systems designed to protect these labile compounds can enhance their stability and
oral dosing efficiency.
2. Extension of Gastric Retention Time: Formulating delivery systems with higher viscosity or the
ability to slow down gastric movement can prolong the residence time of bioactive
compounds in the GI tract. This allows for better absorption before gastric emptying,
increasing the bioavailability of nutraceuticals.
3. Increase Aqueous Solubility: Nutraceuticals need to be solubilized or dispersed in the aqueous
environment to be effectively absorbed by intestinal enterocytes. Delivery systems capable of
enhancing the solubility or dispersion of lipophilic compounds can improve their absorption
and bioavailability.
Common delivery systems used to enhance oral bioavailability include:
• Phospholipid-Based Delivery Systems: Phospholipids, such as those found in liposomes and
phytosomes, are amphipathic lipids that can form lipid bilayers. These delivery systems can
protect bioactive compounds, improve membrane permeability, and enhance absorption,
thereby increasing bioavailability.
• Liposomes: Composed of amphipathic lipid molecules arranged in a bilayer structure with an
aqueous core, liposomes can encapsulate both hydrophilic and lipophilic compounds. This
allows for improved stability and absorption of bioactive compounds like catechin.
• Phytosomes: Phytosomes, also known as phospholipid complexes, are structurally similar to
liposomes but have chemically associated molecules of phosphatidylcholine and natural
active ingredients. This stable complex enhances compound loading capacity and chemical
stability, leading to increased bioavailability compared to unformulated solutions.
13 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
• pH-sensitive delivery systems: pH-sensitive polymers or coatings can be used to target drug
release to specific regions of the gastrointestinal tract, where pH levels vary. This approach
can optimize drug absorption and minimize degradation in the stomach.
• Nanoparticle-based delivery systems: Nanoparticles, including polymeric nanoparticles and
solid lipid nanoparticles, can encapsulate drugs and facilitate their transport across the
intestinal epithelium. These systems can improve drug stability, solubility, and absorption.
Bioequivalence of nutraceuticals involves ensuring that the active ingredients in two or more
identical dosage forms of a nutraceutical product reach the systemic circulation in the body at the
same rate and to the same relative extent. This ensures that different formulations or batches of the
product produce similar pharmacokinetic profiles and physiological effects, thus maintaining
consistency and reliability in their efficacy and safety.
Bioequivalence of nutraceuticals refers to the degree to which two or more formulations of a
nutraceutical product containing the same active ingredients exhibit similar bioavailability and
produce comparable physiological effects in the body when administered under equivalent conditions.
Advantages:
• Ensures Safety and Efficacy: By conducting bioequivalence studies, the pharmaceutical industry
ensures that generic or alternative drugs are as safe and effective as the original product. This is
crucial for maintaining patient health and confidence in the healthcare system.
Disadvantages:
• Requires longer time to complete the studies.
• Completion of studies depends on number of formulations evaluated in the studies.
• Increase in study period leads to high subject dropouts.
• Medical ethics does not allow too many trials on a subject continuously for a longer time.
Requirements/Objectives: -
• If a new product is intended to be a substitute for an approved medicinal product as a
pharmaceutical equivalent or alternative, the equivalence with this product should be shown
or justified.
• In order to ensure clinical performance of such drug products, bioequivalence studies should
be performed.
• Bioequivalence studies are conducted if there is:
• A risk of bio – inequivalence and/or
• A risk of pharmacotherapeutic failure or diminished clinical safety.

Animal models are indispensable tools in biomedical research, aiding in the study of normal biological
processes, the investigation of diseases, and the development and testing of potential treatments.
Here's an overview of the types of animals commonly used in research:
1. Rodent Animal Models:
o Rat: Rats are frequently used due to their physiological and genetic similarities to
humans. They are utilized in a wide range of studies, including neuroscience,
toxicology, and drug development.
o Mice: Mice are the most commonly used animals in research due to their small size,
short reproductive cycle, and ease of genetic manipulation. They are employed in
various fields, such as cancer research, immunology, and genetics.
o Guinea Pigs: Guinea pigs are particularly valuable for studies related to respiratory
diseases, such as asthma and tuberculosis, as well as for certain aspects of
immunology and infectious disease research.
o Hamster: Hamsters are utilized in research related to reproduction, particularly for
studies on fertility and pregnancy.
2. Non-Rodent Animal Models:
o Rabbit: Rabbits are often used in research involving cardiovascular studies, wound
healing, and ocular research due to similarities in anatomy and physiology with
humans.
o Monkey: Primates, including monkeys, are used in neuroscience, behavior studies,
infectious disease research, and drug development due to their close evolutionary
relationship with humans.
o Cat: Cats are utilized in studies of neuroscience, particularly vision and hearing, as
well as in studies of infectious diseases such as HIV.
o Dog: Dogs are employed in various areas of research, including cardiovascular
studies, orthopedics, and pharmaceutical development, owing to their physiological
similarities to humans and their well-characterized genetics.
3. Transgenic Animals:
o Transgenic animals are genetically modified to express specific genes or traits, making
them valuable models for studying human diseases and testing potential therapies.
These animals can be rodents (such as mice and rats) or non-rodents (such as pigs
and rabbits) engineered to mimic human conditions or to serve as platforms for drug
testing and development.
Rats (Rattus norvegicus):
• Valuable for studying analgesics, anticonvulsants, reproductive physiology, gastric acid
secretion, hepatotoxicity, mast cells, and bioassays of hormones.
• Better at removing toxins from their bodies than humans, offering potential refinements in
toxicology studies.
• Rat brain tissue commonly used in radio-receptor ligand studies.
Mice (Mus musculus):
• Widely used in clinical research due to their small size, affordability, and ease of handling.
• Important in fundamental research exploring mammalian physiology, disease mechanisms,
and genetics.
• Similar reproductive and nervous systems to humans, making them valuable for studying
diseases such as cancer, diabetes, and anxiety.
15 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
• Short life span and fast reproductive rate enable investigation of biological processes across
the life cycle.
Rabbit (Oryctolagus cuniculus):
• Historically used in developing the rabies vaccine by Louis Pasteur.
• Key in research areas including cancer, glaucoma, infections, cardiovascular diseases,
diabetes, and emphysema.
• Tolerant to large doses of belladonna (atropine) due to presence of enzyme atropine
esterase.
Monkey (Macaca mulatta):
• Primarily used as primate models to study drug metabolism and psycho-pharmacological
effects.
• Suitable for studying drugs affecting the central nervous system (CNS), cardiovascular system
(CVS), gastrointestinal tract (GIT), and fertility.
• Uterus resembles that of humans, exhibiting regular menstrual cycles.
Creating Transgenic Models:
• Zebrafish mutants utilized to model various human diseases, including Alzheimer’s, congenital
heart diseases, cancers, and nervous system disorders.
• Genetic techniques used to stimulate the development of diseases like T cell acute
lymphoblastic leukemia in zebrafish, enabling testing of anti-cancer agents.
PRECLINICAL TRIALS
• Preclinical trials or non-clinical trials are laboratory test of a new drug substance or medical devices,
usually done on animal subjects, to see whether the treatment really works and if it is safe to test on
humans.
• The main goals of pre-clinical studies are to determine a product's ultimate safety profile.
• Products may include new medical devices, drugs, gene therapy solutions, etc.
➢ initially, experiments typically involve rodents such as mice, rats, guinea pigs, hamsters, and
rabbits.
➢ Upon obtaining positive results, the experiments advance to larger animals like cats, dogs, and
monkeys.
➢ Throughout the evaluation process, compounds are systematically eliminated at each stage if
they demonstrate unfavorable characteristics.
➢ Only a select few, out of the multitude initially considered, advance to the stage where
administration to humans is deemed feasible.
Clinical trials, on the other hand, involve testing the experimental treatment on human volunteers or
patients. Clinical trials typically follow a phased approach:
1. Phase 1: These trials are the first step in testing a new treatment in humans. They focus on
assessing the safety of the treatment, determining the appropriate dosage, and observing any
side effects. Phase 1 trials usually involve a small number of healthy volunteers.
16 | Page N o t e s b y H a y d e n
2. Phase 2: In these trials, the experimental treatment is administered to a larger group of
patients who have the condition or disease that the treatment is intended to address. Phase 2
trials aim to gather preliminary data on the treatment's efficacy and further assess its safety.
3. Phase 3: Phase 3 trials are large-scale studies involving a more extensive patient population.
These trials aim to confirm the treatment's efficacy, monitor side effects, and compare it to
existing standard treatments or a placebo. The data collected in Phase 3 trials are crucial for
regulatory approval by health authorities.
4. Phase 4: Also known as post-marketing surveillance trials, Phase 4 trials occur after the
treatment has been approved and is available to the public. These trials monitor the
treatment's long-term safety and effectiveness in real-world settings and may identify rare
side effects or interactions that were not apparent in earlier phases.
